  "body": "This issue has been reported in various versions and in various forums.\r\n\r\nI can import any openzeppelin contract when I specify its full path (either relative or absolute).\r\n\r\nBut when I start the `import` statement with `'openzeppelin-solidity` as suggested in your official documentation, `truffle compile` is unable to resolve this type of `import` statements.\r\n\r\nI suspect that it might work correctly when Truffle is installed globally (i.e., `npm install truffle -g`), because the official documentation specifies that this is how Truffle should be installed. However, for several (unrelated) reasons, I need to have Truffle installed locally, and so I cannot rely on this for a solution or a workaround.\r\n\r\n**ðŸ’» Environment**\r\n\r\nI am using:\r\n- Truffle v4.1.14 (which relies on solc v0.4.24)\r\n- OpenZeppelin v1.12.0\r\n- Windows 10\r\n\r\n**ðŸ”¢ Code to reproduce bug**\r\n\r\n**Directory Structure:**\r\n- test:\r\n  - node_modules:\r\n    - openzeppelin-solidity:\r\n      - contracts:\r\n        - ownership:\r\n          - Ownable.sol\r\n  - project:\r\n    - contracts:\r\n      - MyContract.sol (see below)\r\n    - truffle-config.js (can be empty)\r\n  - package.json (see below)\r\n\r\n**File MyContract.sol:**\r\n```\r\npragma solidity 0.4.24;\r\nimport \"openzeppelin-solidity/contracts/ownership/Ownable.sol\";\r\ncontract MyContract is Ownable {\r\n    uint public x = 42;\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\n**File package.json:**\r\n```\r\n{\r\n  \"devDependencies\": {\r\n    \"truffle\": \"4.1.14\",\r\n    \"openzeppelin-solidity\": \"1.12.0\"\r\n  }\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\n**Command-line execution:**\r\n```\r\nnpm install\r\ncd project\r\nnode ../node_modules/truffle/build/cli.bundled.js compile\r\n```\r\n\r\nThanks",
